SIMPLE: gleam
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Gleam
<hw>Gleam</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <ety>[Cf. OE.
<ets>glem</ets> birdlime, glue, phlegm, and E.
<ets>englaimed</ets>.]</ety> <fld>(Falconry)</fld> <def>To disgorge
filth, as a hawk.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gleam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Gleam
<hw>Gleam</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE. <ets>glem</ets>,
<ets>gleam</ets>, AS. <ets>gl⟦ae⟧m</ets>, prob. akin to E.
<ets>glimmer</ets>, and perh. to Gr. <?/ warm, <?/ to warm. Cf.
<er>Glitter</er>.]</ety>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>1.</sn> <def>A shoot of light; a small stream of light; a beam; a
ray; a glimpse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Transient unexpected <qex>gleams</qex> of joi.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>At last a <qex>gleam</qex>⟦br⟧
Of dawning light turned thitherward in haste⟦br⟧
His [Satan's] traveled steps.</q> <rj><qau>Milton.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>A glimmer, and then a <qex>gleam</qex> of light.</q>
<rj><qau>Longfellow.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Brightness; splendor.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In the clear azure <qex>gleam</qex> the flocks are seen.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gleam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Gleam
<hw>Gleam</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Gleamed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Gleaming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To shoot, or dart,
as rays of light; <as>as, at the dawn, light <ex>gleams</ex> in the
east</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To shine; to cast light; to glitter.</def></p>

<p><syn><b>Syn.</b> -- To <er>Gleam</er>, <er>Glimmer</er>,
<er>Glitter</er>.</syn> <usage> To <xex>gleam</xex> denotes a faint but
distinct emission of light. To <xex>glimmer</xex> describes an
indistinct and unsteady giving of light. To <xex>glitter</xex> imports a
brightness that is intense, but varying. The morning light
<xex>gleams</xex> upon the earth; a distant taper <xex>glimmers</xex>
through the mist; a dewdrop <xex>glitters</xex> in the sun. See
<er>Flash</er>.</usage>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gleam</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Gleam
<hw>Gleam</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To shoot out (flashes of light,
etc.).</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Dying eyes <qex>gleamed</qex> forth their ashy lights.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Gleamy</ent>⟦br⟧
